location: NW Twin Cites, MN, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Available is a classic Smith & Wesson Heavy Duty .38/.44 revolver manufactured 1933 (Pre WW-II).  Has a 5 inch barrel and is a 5-Screw model.  All serial numbers (#431xx) match on barrel, frame and cylinder.  Original finish is approximately 75-80%.  Lock up is tight.  Rifling is sharp.  Has factory S&W roll stamp, "Reg. U.S Pat. Off." on hammer (Rare).  Factory grooved trigger.  Last factory roll stamp, on barrel top, is "Dec 29, '14"

This model was built in response to law enforcement's requirement for an arm that would shoot a high speed round which could penetrate car bodies and bullet proof vests.  The collaboration between Smith & Wesson, Remington and Elmer Keith produced the 38/44 S&W cartridge which could launch a 158 grain bullet at 1175 fps and producing 460 foot pounds of energy.  This round would penetrate 11-7/8 inch thick boards and would go thru the trunk of a car, seats, dash and into the engine area.  The factory first offered this gun in a 5 inch barrel, blue or nickel finish and service stocks.   The 38/44 Heavy Duty was the father of the .357 Registered Magnum which appeared in 1935.  

Asking $675.00 or Best Offer.  Buyer must have MN I.D., along with either a MN CCW Permit or MN Purchase Permit.  Also buyer must sign Bill of Sale.  NO EXCEPTIONS.  Any questions or interest.  Please contact me.  Thank you,

Introduced to the firearms market in 1927, the Colt Official Police is a medium frame, double-action revolver with a six-round cylinder, primarily chambered for the .38 Special cartridge, and manufactured by the Colt's Manufacturing Company. The intended specific target market for the Official Police was mainly law enforcement agencies and it became one of the best selling police firearms of all time, eventually in the 1950s coming to exemplify typical peace officer weaponry. The Official Police was also used by various U.S. and allied military forces during World War II.

postcontent:
Available is a classic Colt Official Police, MK III in .38 Special.  (Mfg'd 1970).  All numbers match on the revolver.  Original finish is excellent, except of 1/4 of the cylinder has lost all bluing.  Likely from a holster.  There is some lite holster wear on the barrel muzzle too.  Original Colt Grips are in great shape.  This was a Wis. County Sheriff's carry piece.  

The moniker “Official Police” was borrowed by this model in a new generation of revolvers Colt introduced in the late 1960s, called the “MK III” series. MK III models consisted of simpler versions of several classic Colt revolvers with updated lock work. The MK III product line was actually a different and original design based on a new “J” frame and was only available for three years.

Asking $450.00 or Best Offer.  Buyer must have MN I.D., along with either a MN CCW Permit or MN Purchase Permit.  Also, Buyer must sign Bill of Sale.  NO EXCEPTIONS.  Any questions or interest.  Please contact me.  Thank you.

title: For Sale:  Rare GERMAN SCHMEISSER 25 acp Pistol NAZI CG Haenel AK47 Designer!
postcontent:
This is the Model 1 SCHMEISSER PISTOLE 25 acp, made at the CG Haenel Factory in Suhl, Germany in the 1920-30's.  Designed by Hugo Schmeisser, the designer of the infamous MP40 Submachine Gun used by the NAZI's in WW2, and also the actual designer of the AK47 Kalasnikov rifle (as recently declassified Russian/Nazi documents prove). Kalashnikov was a simple corporal assigned to assist Schmeisser in the rifle development program for the USSR after WW2 ended. We got Von Braun and a space program, and the Russians got Hugo Schmeisser's AK47 and the most robust battle rifle ever made in history. And Mikhail Kalashnikov got the credit and fame for being the Russian inventor. True story!

The Haenel factory in Suhl made these pistols before the war, and the ones sold for export outside of Germany had Made in Germany stamped on the slide. This one was made for sale to German citizens, in Germany, and doesn't have that stamp. Very few were sold in Germany before the war, as a gentlemen's pocket pistol was a luxury item that few Germans could afford. Most of these domestic Schmeisser 25 acp guns ended up in the uniforms of high-ranking NAZI Officers and members of the Wehrmacht, and elite SS troops, as they were a highly prized backup gun for their Luger sidearms.

This one is exceptional, with all matching numbers, an original magazine, and original grips.  It has an outstanding plum-brown original patina, and hasn't been refinished. And it fires and functions perfectly.

It would make an outstanding addition to any advanced German auto pistol collection.
I have more collectors information, and photos available concerning markings, proof marks, and model variations if you desire in PDF form.

I'm asking for $550 cash sales to local collectors, but I will also transfer out of state FFL to FFL if the buyer pays those fees and shipping costs.

Thanks for looking!

I will also consider trades for other guns of similar value for my collection.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Two Mauser Chileno Modelo 1895 Rifles
postcontent:
Two Sporter rifles. One looks to be a numbers-matching Mauser Chileno Modelo 1895 Carbine that has been professionally sporterized. The bayonet lug, cleaning rod and attachment is gone and the hole for it in the stock has been plugged. I am told by someone who purports to know these guns (without seeing them) that it has been rebarreled to .308 and indeed several boxes of .308 came with it. I don't know if I believe that, and you will need to find a gunsmith to verify or disprove it before firing it. It looks to be an original barely-used rifle, I won't be surprised considering the source if it was un-issued which was at some distant time sporterized by a gunsmith who knew what he was doing. It has a modern rail mount with a 3x9 Hailey's Optics scope and a bent bolt.
The other I cannot identify exactly. It has the Mauser Chileno Modelo 1895 receiver, stamped 7.62N on the receiver bridge, but I have searched the internet and cannot find a long barrel - long stock rifle like it. The wood, for example, extends above and below the barrel longer than anything I see depicted on the net or in Mauser books and the barrel is quite a bit longer than even the long rifle pictures I can find. All of the pics I find show the top forestock ending at the sling band, as the carbine's does. The long rifle top piece extends to the full forestock. Like the other rifle the bayonet lug and cleaning rod have been removed. This one has a beautifully done Chilean 1895 acceptance cartouche on the stock. This bolt is straight.
I bought these from a cousin who inherited them from his father last month, who was a professional art restorer. Whoever did the work on these rifles did as good a job as I have ever seen. Unless you knew they were supposed to have a bayonet and cleaning rod or that they have been sporterized you couldn't tell it...this is certainly no Bubba job.
Both are dirty but inside the barrels are clean, excellent rifling (looks almost as-new to me) and their overall condition is excellent with no significant rust or damage. they look as if they were oiled then stuck in someone's gun case for the last 125 years.

I may keep the long rifle simply because it has the most beautiful stock I have ever seen. With the stock style and long continuous grain in the wood, and the elegant overall lines, this is the prettiest gun I have ever seen, well worth owning as a piece of art. In that case I will take $300 for the scoped carbine.

Being made in 1895 these are Antigues that do not need FFL transfer registration.
